ed kidneys may have difficulty processing high protein loads."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does protein help with weight loss?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. Protein has the highest thermic effect of all macronutrients (20-30% of protein calories are used in digestion). It also promotes satiety more than carbohydrates or fat, reducing overall calorie intake. During a calorie deficit, higher protein intake (1.2-1.6 g per kg) helps preserve lean muscle mass, which keeps metabolic rate higher."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What are the best high-protein foods?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The best high-protein foods include chicken breast (31g per 100g cooked), canned tuna (26g per 100g), eggs (13g per 100g), Greek yoghurt (10g per 100g), cottage cheese (12g per 100g), lentils (9g per 100g cooked), tofu (8g per 100g), and beef (26g per 100g cooked). Whey protein powder provides 70-80g per 100g but is a supplement, not a whole food."}}]}]});

